https://t.co/TFwckNgMUz

ICYMI: We often hear about the Bank of Mum and Dad, but in low and middle income families some parents  depend on their children to bring money in

@bola_sol writes about what she’s dubbed “The Bank of Children”

https://t.co/b5HBUpN9F4

ICYMI: Like Bruce Willis, Colin Lyall had to leave a successful career when he was diagnosed with aphasia. It left him frustrated and bored, but with the support of his loved ones, he’s found purpose in helping others

@sayaphasia

https://t.co/6JjPYjQde1

‘If I could say one thing to government, it would be do not ignore the needs of the minority to feed the majority,’ she writes in @TheHouseMag 

‘Thousands feel like they're the underdogs, begging for the system to give them the chances that are rightfully theirs’

@juliejaye07

@IamStrappa The irony is that the people he’s mocking, are probably miles smarter than him both in terms of academic intelligence and social skill

I could be wrong, but I would bet money on this

(This doesn’t take away from the fact that Priti Patel is problematic at best, evil at worst)

@judeblay I hear your point about passion and honing a craft over time, because it’s so important. 

At the same time, I think we have to be careful about glorifying the struggle/period where your art doesn’t pay. 

It normalises it instead of asking us to question unjust systems I think.

@dkaycapalot You know what, the rhetoric behind that tweet and the fact that men really do do that still stands. If anything, it just shows it’s so pervasive within our culture. 

But I acknowledge I didn’t know it was a lyric. 

Enjoy the rest of your day.

